<para>
  Reduce noise in an image by apply a median filter.  This replaces
  the value of each pixel with the median value in a circle of the
  given <varname>radius</varname> centered on the pixel.  The
  <varname>radius</varname> is in units of the pixel size.  For a
  color image, each RGB channel is filtered independently.
</para>
<para>
  This routine calls the <ulink
  url="https://scikit-image.org/docs/stable/api/skimage.filters.html#skimage.filters.median"
  role="external"><code>skimage.filters.median</code></ulink> from the
  &skimage; library.
</para>
<figure id="Figure-MedianFilter">
  <title>Applying a Median Filter to an Image</title>
  <mediaobject>
    <imageobject>
	  <imagedata fileref="FIGURES/imageops/noise.png" format="PNG"/>
    </imageobject>
    <caption>
	  <para>
	    A micrograph of
	    Si<subscript>3</subscript>N<subscript>4</subscript>
	    (courtesy of C.-H. Hsueh), with noise added.
	  </para>
    </caption>
  </mediaobject>
  <mediaobject>
    <imageobject>
	  <imagedata fileref="FIGURES/imageops/median2.png" format="PNG"/>
    </imageobject>
    <caption>
	  <para>
	    The result of applying <command>Median</command> with
	    <varname>radius</varname>=2.
	  </para>
    </caption>
  </mediaobject>
  <mediaobject>
    <imageobject>
	  <imagedata fileref="FIGURES/imageops/median5.png" format="PNG"/>
    </imageobject>
    <caption>
	  <para>
	    The result of applying <command>Median</command> with
	    <varname>radius</varname>=5.
	  </para>
    </caption>
  </mediaobject>
</figure>

